<subsection xml:id="subsec-SingleMeanTestPractice">
  <title>Practice Problems</title>

 
<exercise xml:id="oceanpH-hypothesis-test">
  <title> Change in Ocean pH</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Scientists have long used a historical average surface ocean pH of about
      <m>8.20</m> as a benchmark. Recent National Ocean and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) summaries report that global surface
      ocean pH has decreased by about <m>0.1</m> to <m>0.11</m> units since the
      Industrial Revolution, suggesting modern ocean pH may now be lower on average.
    </p>
    <p>
      A marine science team collects a random sample of <m>16</m> recent surface-ocean
      pH measurements from one region and obtains a sample mean of
      <m>\bar{x}=8.08</m> and a sample standard deviation of <m>s=0.12</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, test whether the true mean ocean pH
      in this region has changed from the historical value of <m>8.20</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      State the null and alternative hypotheses, compute the test statistic,
      estimate the <term>p-value</term>, and state a conclusion in context.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <hint>
    <p>
      Because the population standard deviation is unknown, use a one-sample
      <m>t</m>-test for the mean.
    </p>
    <p>
      For the question of whether the pH has <q>changed</q>, use a two-sided test:
    </p>
    <p> <m>H_0:\mu=8.20 \qquad H_a: \mu\ne 8.20 </m> </p>
    <p>
      Then compute
    </p>
    <p> <md>t=\frac{\bar{x}-\mu_0}{s/\sqrt{n}}.</md> </p>
  </hint>
  <answer>
    <p> The hypotheses are <m>H_0:\mu=8.20</m> and <m>H_a: \mu \ne 8.20</m>.
      The test statistic is <m>t=-3.88</m> with <m>df=15</m>.
      The two-sided <term>p-value</term> is <m>0.0017</m>.
      Since the <em>p-value</em> is less than 0.05, we reject <m>H_0</m>.
      Conclude there is significant evidence that the mean ocean pH in this region has changed from 8.    </p>
  </answer>
  <solution>
    <p> We test whether the population mean pH differs from the historical benchmark
      of <m>8.20</m>.     </p>
    <p> The hypotheses are    
    <m> H_0:\mu=8.20 \qquad H_a:\mu\ne 8.20.</m> </p>
    <p> Because the population standard deviation is unknown and the sample size is
      16, we use a one-sample <m>t</m>-test.    </p>
    <p> The standard error is     
    <md>\frac{s}{\sqrt{n}}=\frac{0.12}{\sqrt{16}}=\frac{0.12}{4}=0.03.</md> </p>
    <p> The test statistic is     </p>
    <p> <md>t=\frac{8.08-8.20}{0.03}=\frac{-0.12}{0.03}=-4.00.</md> </p>
    <p> The degrees of freedom are <m>df=16-1=15.</m> </p>
    <p> A test statistic of <m>t=-3.89</m> with <m>15</m> degrees of freedom gives a two-sided <term>p-value</term> <m>=2(.0018)=.0036</m>.     </p>
    <p> Since the <term>p-value</term> is less than the significance level
      <m>\alpha=0.05</m>, we reject the null hypothesis.     </p>
    <p>
      There is sufficient statistical evidence to conclude that the true mean
      ocean pH in this region has changed from the historical value of <m>8.20</m>.
      Because the sample mean is lower than <m>8.20</m>, the data suggests the change
      is a decrease in pH level.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="oceanDecph-hypothesis-test">
  <title> Decreasing in Ocean pH</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Scientists have historically used an average surface ocean pH of about
      <m>8.20</m> as a benchmark. Recent NOAA summaries indicate that average
      surface ocean pH has decreased over time, motivating a test of whether
      the mean pH in a particular region is now lower than <m>8.20</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      A marine science team collects a random sample of <m>12</m> recent
      surface-ocean pH measurements from one coastal region:
    </p>
    <p>
      <m>8.07,\; 8.12,\; 8.05,\; 8.10,\; 8.09,\; 8.03,\; 8.11,\; 8.06,\; 8.08,\; 8.04,\; 8.13,\; 8.07</m>
    </p>
    <p>
      At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, test whether the true mean ocean pH
      in this region has decreased from the historical value of <m>8.20</m>.
    </p>
    <p> State the null and alternative hypotheses, compute the test statistic,
      estimate the <em>p-value</em>, and state a conclusion in context.    </p>
  </statement>
  <hint>
    <p> Use a one-sample <m>t</m>-test for a population mean, since the population
      standard deviation is unknown.     </p>
    <p>  For a one-sided test of decrease, use     </p>
    <p> <md>H_0: \mu=8.20 \qquad H_a: \mu \lt 8.20.</md> </p>
    <p> Then compute the sample mean, sample standard deviation, and test statistic  </p>
    <p> <md>t=\frac{\bar{x}-\mu_0}{s/\sqrt{n}}.</md> </p>
  </hint>
  <answer>
    <p>
      The hypotheses are <m>H_0:\mu=8.20</m> and <m>H_a: \mu \lt 8.20</m>.
      From the data, <m>\bar{x}\approx 8.079</m> and <m>s \approx 0.033</m>.
      The test statistic is <m>t\approx -12.59</m> with
      <m>df=11</m>. The <em>p-value</em> is effectively <m>0</m>
      (far less than <m>0.05</m>), so we reject <m>H_0</m>.
      There is strong evidence that the true mean ocean pH in this region
      has decreased below <m>8.20</m>.
    </p>
  </answer>
  <solution>
    <p> We want to test whether the population mean ocean pH is lower than
      the historical benchmark of <m>8.20</m>.     </p>
    <p> The hypotheses are     
    <md> H_0:\mu=8.20 \qquad H_a:\mu \lt 8.20     </md> </p>
    <p>       Because the population standard deviation is unknown, we use a one-sample
      <m>t</m>-test for the mean.     </p>
    <p>  First compute the sample statistics from the data:    </p>
    <p> <md>\bar{x}=\frac{8.07+8.12+8.05+8.10+8.09+8.03+8.11+8.06+8.08+8.04+8.13+8.07}{12}\approx 8.079.</md> </p>
    <p> <md>s\approx 0.033.</md> </p>
    <p>       The sample size is <m>n=12</m>, so the degrees of freedom are  <m>df=12-1=11.</m> </p>
    <p> The standard error is     
    <md>\frac{s}{\sqrt{n}} \approx \frac{0.033}{\sqrt{12}} \approx 0.0095.</md> </p>
    <p>       The test statistic is     
    <md>t=\frac{\bar{x}-\mu_0}{s/\sqrt{n}}=\frac{8.079-8.20}{0.0095}\approx -12.77.</md> </p>
    <p>
      With <m>df=11</m>, this gives a one-sided <term>p-value</term> that is
      extremely small, far below <m>0.05</m>.
    </p>
    <p>       Therefore, we reject <m>H_0</m>.     </p>
    <p>       There is strong statistical evidence that the true mean ocean pH in this
      region has decreased below <m>8.20</m>.     </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>




  </subsection>






</section> 